    <text>
        <body>       

                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>The sentiment which impels us to part with<lb/> some of our means&#44; that we may relieve want&#44; en&#45;<lb/>nobles human nature&#44; yet our generous impulses<lb/> are apt to lead to injury.  Deception <del>often</del> lays<lb/> them under tribute to its own advantage&#59; <del>and</del> idle<lb/> pauperism <del>is encouraged pli&#91;&#63;&#93;</del> succeeds too often to its trade unblushed.  Organized charity&#44;<lb/> seeking into the condition of the needy&#44; and joining<lb/> a friendly advice to the discreetly given help&#44;<lb/> commends itself to all the right&#45;thinking Phila&#45;<lb/>delphians can point to their men and women engaged<lb/> in so beneficently <del>allocating</del> working&#44; to <del>alleviate mi others suffering</del> mitigate the ills<lb/> &#45;<del>sery</del> of life.  The society in whose behalf those public<lb/> almoners labor has proved its efficacy in numberless<lb/> instances&#44; when the plans of the artful were frustrated&#44;<lb/> the modest poor <del>found support</del> met with a sympathetic hearing&#44;<lb/> the industrious found encouragement&#44; the sick <del>and</del><lb/> <del>the aged timely attendance</del> a kindly ministration&#44; &#38; the virtuous were shielded<lb/> by <del>kindly men</del> timely aid.  A <del></del>society corporation so <del>well or rightly</del><lb/> <del>ganized</del> sensibly &#38; usefully governed deserves the continued confidence&#44; and intelligent<lb/> cooperation of the whole community.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>My dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>Not knowing precisely what might<lb/> be acceptable at my hands&#44; I wrote the few<lb/> lines here subjoined.  I judge they were to be<lb/> brief&#44; I made them so.  If they don&#39;t answer&#44; let them go into the waste basket.  Having in my mind<lb/> some of the reports&#45;&#45;I am sorry I could not find<lb/> a single number just now&#45;&#45;I thought I was justified in com&#45;<lb/>mending the work.  Besides&#44; you are my authority<lb/> for its having merited the praise of the charitable.<lb/>  Yours truly<lb/> S. Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>Lucien Moss Esq<lb/>
                Nov 15.&#47;88<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
